  "description": "Common chemical elements, tested both ways: symbol → name and name → symbol, tracked separately. Grouped by where they sit in the periodic table.",
  "primerTitle": "Reading the periodic table",
  "primer": "The **periodic table** arranges elements by increasing **atomic number** $Z$ (number of protons). Each element has a one- or two-letter **symbol** and a **name**. This deck tests both directions — symbol → name and name → symbol — for common elements.\n\n### How it's organised\n\n- **Periods** — the horizontal rows.\n- **Groups** — the vertical columns; elements in a group share chemical behaviour.\n- This deck groups the cards by family: **alkali & alkaline-earth metals**, **transition metals**, **other metals**, **non-metals & metalloids**, **halogens**, and **noble gases**.\n\n### The recall method\n\nMost symbols are just the first letter (or first two) of the English name — **H**ydrogen, **C**arbon, **Ca**lcium. A handful come from **Latin** names and must be memorised separately:\n\n| Symbol | Element | From |\n|---|---|---|\n| Na | Sodium | natrium |\n| K | Potassium | kalium |\n| Fe | Iron | ferrum |\n| Cu | Copper | cuprum |\n| Ag | Silver | argentum |\n| Sn | Tin | stannum |\n| Au | Gold | aurum |\n| Hg | Mercury | hydrargyrum |\n| Pb | Lead | plumbum |\n\n### A high-frequency subset\n\n- **Non-metals:** H (hydrogen), C (carbon), N (nitrogen), O (oxygen), P (phosphorus), S (sulfur), Si (silicon).\n- **Halogens:** F (fluorine), Cl (chlorine), Br (bromine), I (iodine).\n- **Noble gases:** He (helium), Ne (neon), Ar (argon).\n- **Alkali / alkaline-earth:** Li, Na, K (alkali); Mg, Ca (alkaline-earth).\n- **Transition metals:** Fe (iron), Cu (copper), Zn (zinc), Ag (silver), Au (gold), Pt (platinum).\n\nThis is a representative sample, not the full list — *the deck's cards cover more elements than are enumerated here, so work through the cards for the complete set.*",
